# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-ram-van
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-ram-van/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:dodge-ram-van/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In the automotive industry, **rebadging** (also known as **badge engineering**, an intentionally ironic misnomer in that little or no actual engineering takes place) is a form of market segmentation used by automobile manufacturers around the world.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] To allow for product differentiation without designing or engineering a new model or brand (at high cost or risk), a manufacturer creates a distinct automobile by applying a new "badge" or trademark (brand, logo, or manufacturer's name/make/marque) to an existing product line.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The term originated with the practice of replacing an automobile's emblems to create an ostensibly new model sold by a different maker.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Changes may be confined to swapping badges and emblems, or may encompass minor styling differences, as with cosmetic changes to headlights, taillights, front and rear fascias, and even outer body skins.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] More extreme examples involve differing engines and drivetrains.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The objective is "to spread the huge development costs of a new vehicle over as many cars as possible".
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] An example is General Motors' rebadging of the Camaro as the Firebird, a successful model from the 1960s through to the 2000s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In most cases, consumers are interested in each brand's focus "on the unique elements of styling and driving characteristics".
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Some cars would not be marketed without the cost savings that are obtained from this practice, and carmakers can develop many "different models – all wearing different badges – off the one platform".
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In several countries including Japan, manufacturers often use the phrase "OEM supply" or "OEM-supplied" to denote vehicles that are a rebadged model from or for other manufacturers.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Although platform sharing can often involve rebadging and rebranding, it can extend further, as the design may be used across multiple configurations.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] For example, a single platform may underpin a sedan, hatchback, or SUV/CUV body designs.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Automotive industry rebadging can be compared with white-label products in other consumer goods industries, such as consumer electronics and power tools.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The first known case of badge engineering appeared in 1917 with the Texan automobile assembled in Fort Worth, Texas, that made use of Elcar bodies made in Elkhart, Indiana.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] "Probably the industry's first example of one car becoming another" occurred in 1926 when Nash Motors' newly introduced smaller-sized Ajax models were discontinued in 1926 after over 22,000 Ajax cars were sold during the brand's inaugural year.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The chairman and CEO of the company, Charles W.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Nash, ordered that the Ajax models be marketed as the "Nash Light Six", Nash being a known and respected automobile brand.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Production was stopped for two days so Nash emblems, hubcaps, and radiator shells could be exchanged on all unshipped Ajax cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Conversion kits were also distributed at no charge to Ajax owners to transform their cars and protect the investment they had made in purchasing an automobile made by Nash.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Starting with the beginning of General Motors in 1909, chassis and platforms were shared with all brands.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] GMC, which historically was a truck builder, began to offer its products branded as Chevrolet, and vehicles produced by GM were built on common platforms shared with Chevrolet, Oakland, Oldsmobile, Buick, and Cadillac.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Exterior appearances were gradually upgraded between these vehicle brands.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] This was partly because all bodywork was provided by Fisher Body which was bought by GM in 1925, and the introduction of the Art and Color Section in 1928, directed by Harley Earl.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] For the 1958 model year, GM was promoting its fiftieth year of production and introduced anniversary models for each brand; Cadillac, Buick, Oldsmobile, Pontiac, and Chevrolet.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The 1958 models shared an almost identical appearance on all models for each brand and made special luxury models with a shared appearance; Cadillac Eldorado Seville, Buick Limited Riviera, Oldsmobile Starfire 98, Pontiac Bonneville Catalina, and the Chevrolet Bel-Air Impala.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] A later example was Wolseley Motors after it was bought out by William Morris.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] After World War I, "Wolseley started to lose its identity and eventually succumbed to badge engineering." This was repeated with the consolidation of Austin Motor Company and the Nuffield Organization (parent company of Morris Motors) to form the British Motor Corporation (BMC).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The rationalization of production to gain efficiencies "did not extend to marketing", and each "model was adapted, by variation in trim and accessories, to appeal to customer loyalties for whom the badge denoting the company of origin was an important selling advantage ...
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] 'Badge Engineering', as it became known, was symptomatic of a policy of sales competition between the constituent organizations".
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The ultimate example of BMC badge engineering was the 1962 BMC ADO16 which was available badged as a Morris, MG, Austin, Wolseley, Riley and the upmarket Vanden Plas.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] A year earlier, the Mini was also available as Austin, Morris, Riley, and Wolseley – the latter two having slightly bigger boots.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Badge engineering often occurs when an individual manufacturer (such as the regional Big Threes of the United States, Europe, and Japan) owns a portfolio of different brands and markets the same car under different brands and nameplates.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The practice is used for multiple reasons.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In one example, a company may do so to expand its range of different brands in a market without the cost of developing completely new models.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In the United States, General Motors may sell a car through each brand; for example, the Chevrolet Tahoe, GMC Yukon, and Cadillac Escalade each share a common body.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In another example, the same model is rebadged when it is sold in different regions and markets.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In Australia, during the 1980s and 1990s, the Button car plan required imported Nissans and Toyotas to adopt Ford and Holden (GM) nameplates.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In the United Kingdom, Opel-produced vehicles are marketed under the Vauxhall brand; when sold in the United States, Opels were marketed as Saturns, Chevrolets, and Buicks.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Conversely, the Australian Holden brand was never sold in North America, but the Holden Monaro and Holden Commodore were sold under the Pontiac (Pontiac GTO, Pontiac G8), Chevrolet (Chevrolet SS), and Buick (Buick Regal Sportback/Buick Regal TourX) nameplates.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Another way badge engineering may occur is when two separate manufacturers trade products, filling gaps in their respective product lineups.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] During the 1990s, Honda and Isuzu entered into such an agreement, with Isuzu marketing the first-generation Honda Odyssey as the Isuzu Oasis as its first minivan.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] During the late 2000s and early 2010s, the Volkswagen Routan was a rebranded version of the Dodge Grand Caravan, supplied as Volkswagen sought to re-enter the North American minivan segment without the investment of federalizing its design.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Assembled by Chrysler with a Chrysler powertrain, the Routan received its own styling and content features as well as a standard "sportier suspension and steering".
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] (right) are two mechanically, internally, and near-externally identical cars that share the majority of their components, however feature various different stylistic elements to cater to the design language of each brand.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In Japan, automobile manufacturers differed in the marketing of their product ranges.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In contrast to marketing a single vehicle under multiple brand names (with minor changes to exterior bodywork), Japanese manufacturers marketed vehicles through multiple sales networks, with a distinct vehicle being sold under various model nameplates (from a single manufacturer).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Toyota marketed the Corolla in Japan exclusively at *Toyota Corolla Store* locations; at *Toyota Auto Store* locations, it was named the Toyota Sprinter.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Nissan sold the Nissan Cedric through its *Nissan Bluebird Store* network, with the identical Nissan Gloria through the *Nissan Prince Store* network.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Honda previously marketed the Honda Accord through multiple sales networks, marketing the Accord through the *Honda Clio* network and renaming it as the Honda Vigor for *Honda Verno* locations (conversely, the Vigor was renamed the Honda Inspire for the Clio network).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The practice of producing multiple versions of the same vehicle would eventually lead to distinct vehicles produced for export.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In North America, the Toyota Sprinter was marketed as the Chevrolet Nova (and the Geo Prizm that replaced it).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The Honda Vigor and Inspire were marketed as the Acura Vigor and TL; Nissan sold the Gloria in the United States as the Infiniti M45.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Two automakers can also pool resources by operating a joint venture to create a product and then selling each as their own.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] For example, General Motors and Toyota formed NUMMI.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The vehicles produced from this venture (though not necessarily at NUMMI itself) included the Toyota Sprinter/Chevrolet Prizm, and later the Toyota Matrix/Pontiac Vibe.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In another agreement, Ford and Nissan developed and produced the Mercury Villager and Nissan Quest minivans from 1993 through 2002.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Another example was the cooperative work between Volkswagen and Ford to develop the VW Sharan, Ford Galaxy, and SEAT Alhambra.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Another example was the joint venture of Mitsubishi and Chrysler that resulted in vehicles produced by Diamond-Star Motors that were marketed under various nameplates from 1985 until 1993.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In China, foreign manufacturers were required to form a joint venture with a local manufacturer to manufacture automobiles in the country.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Prior to 2022, the Chinese government dictates that no more than two joint ventures are allowed for each foreign investor.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Larger foreign manufacturers often set up two joint ventures to maximize the market reach, including Toyota (FAW Toyota and GAC Toyota), Ford (JMC-Ford and Changan Ford), Volkswagen (SAIC-VW and FAW-VW) and Honda (Dongfeng Honda and Guangqi Honda).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] To distribute the production and sales rights to each joint venture, manufacturers often resort to a similar strategy deployed in Japan: simply producing the exact model under two different names with minor changes to exterior bodywork.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] GAC Toyota has produced the Levin as a twin model to the FAW Toyota-built Corolla and the Wildlander as the alternative to the RAV4.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Honda awarded several models to two joint ventures, which spawned the Breeze from the original CR-V, the Elysion from the Odyssey, the XR-V from the HR-V, and others.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In other cases, foreign manufacturers may also rebadge a model developed by its partner, sometimes for exports to other markets.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Examples include the second generation Chevrolet Captiva which is an export version of the Baojun 530 made by SAIC-GM-Wuling, or the Ford Territory, a reworked version of the Yusheng S330 developed by Jiangling Motors (JMC).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Badge engineering could be used as a strategy to lengthen the life cycle of a vehicle.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] After a product has reached the end of its life cycle, it may be transferred to another brand, mostly from the same holding company or joint venture.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Examples include the SEAT Exeo, a rebadged Audi A4 B7 with reworked styling, which was built in Spain from used production tooling from the Audi plant in Ingolstadt after the A4 B7 production had ended.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The tooling was dismantled from Ingolstadt and was sent to the SEAT manufacturing plant in Martorell, Spain, to be reinstalled.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Another example is the Dongfeng Fengdu MX6, which was produced after the near-identical Nissan X-Trail (T31) production had ended, and the Maruti Suzuki Zen Estilo, which is based on the then-recently discontinued Suzuki MR Wagon.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The advantage of this strategy is amortized tooling costs, which means the vehicle can be produced at a higher margin of profit (or a lower price, or both).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Badge engineering occurs in the luxury-type market segments.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] An automobile manufacturer will use a model from its mainstream brand as a basis for a model under a premium marque by upgrading its features, technology, and/or styling.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Along with visible cosmetic differences, premium models may also receive upgraded drivetrains.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] An example of this is that Ford Motor Company marketed its mainstream Ford Fusion mid-size sedan as the Lincoln MKZ; the Ford Expedition SUV is sold as the Lincoln Navigator.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] A more controversial example was the Aston Martin Cygnet, a rebadged version of the Toyota iQ city car (intended to comply with EU emissions regulations).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] While fitted with model-specific trim and a luggage set, the Cygnet nearly tripled the price of the iQ.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Alternatively, VW Group under Ferdinand Piëch used the reverse of this in some circumstances, engineering the more luxurious model first and then removing features for models from less prestigious marques.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Examples include the Lamborghini Gallardo/Audi R8 and the Audi A4/Volkswagen Passat.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Along with rebadging and badge engineering, platform sharing is common throughout the automotive industry.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Alongside a shared chassis (though unibody construction is nearly universal in cars and many light trucks), platform sharing also standardizes components such as drivetrain, suspensions, components, and other technologies.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] General Motors used the B platform for many of its non-Cadillac full-size vehicles (nearly exclusively from 1959 through 1985), while Chrysler used its B platform for intermediates and its C platform for (non-Imperial) full-size cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The Volkswagen Group uses platform sharing as its business strategy to improve its profitability and growth.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] For example, Audi uses components from their more pedestrian counterparts, sold as Volkswagen mass-market brands.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] As an effort to place Audi as a "premium" marque, Volkswagen often introduces new technologies in Audi-branded cars before fitting them to mainstream products (such as the Direct-Shift Gearbox).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In production, platform sharing is used extensively, with the modular MQB platform underpinning a range of vehicles from the Audi A1 to the Volkswagen Atlas.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The previous D platform of the 2000s was used for the Volkswagen Phaeton and Bentley Continental GT (built in steel) and the Audi A8 (built in aluminum).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In the Japanese automotive industry, platform sharing has expanded model offerings in North America.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] While the initial Lexus LS was developed specifically for the American market, the later Lexus ES has shared a platform (but not a body) with the Toyota Camry (since 2013, the Toyota Avalon, itself also based on the Camry).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Exclusive primarily to North America, Honda uses a common platform to produce the American version of the Odyssey minivan, also underpinning the Honda Pilot and Honda Passport SUVs, the Acura MDX CUV, and the Honda Ridgeline mid-size pickup truck.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] , originally used by the VE series Holden Commodore.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Although rebadging is intended to save development costs by spreading design and research expenses across several vehicles, it can become problematic if not implemented properly.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Utilizing multiple car brands under a single parent manufacturer can significantly increase selling costs, as each model line must be marketed separately, necessitating a distinct dealership network.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Inappropriate use of rebadging can also negatively impact overall sales by causing "cannibalism" between two or more brands owned by the same company.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] This can occur when there is a failure to develop a distinct image for each brand or when the failure of one version of a model adversely affects its rebadged counterparts.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Through the 2000s, the American Big Three automakers reduced their brand footprint by closing or selling underperforming brands.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] After 2001, Chrysler discontinued its Plymouth brand (following the closure of Eagle in 1998).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In response to the late 2000s recession, Ford ended its ownership of Jaguar, Land Rover, Aston Martin, and Volvo Cars; in 2010, Mercury was closed by Ford.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] General Motors underwent several brand revisions; following the discontinuation of the Geo sub-brand of Chevrolet in 1997, Oldsmobile was closed after 2004 (the oldest American nameplate at the time).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Following its 2009 bankruptcy, GM closed Pontiac, Saturn, and Hummer in 2010; Saab was sold (eventually leading to its demise).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] GM sold its European Opel and Vauxhall brands in 2017 to PSA (now Stellantis).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In response to the 1973 oil crisis, General Motors expanded fuel-efficient offerings beyond its Chevrolet division, reintroducing compact cars to its Buick, Oldsmobile, and Pontiac brands.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Derived from the X-platform Chevrolet Nova, the Pontiac Ventura was introduced for the 1971 model year, with the Buick Apollo and Oldsmobile Omega introduced for 1973.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] These four X-platform vehicles (also known as N-O-V-A from the first letters of their model names) were produced with identical bodies with divisional differences marked only with specific grille, lamp, and body trim variations.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] To expand its footprint in the subcompact segment, the H-body Chevrolet Vega platform was used for the 1975 model year for newly styled variants sold as the Chevrolet Monza, Buick Skyhawk, and Oldsmobile Starfire followed by the 1976 Pontiac Sunbird.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Similarly, to the X-body vehicles, the H-body subcompacts shared common bodies across all four divisions with differing grille, lamp, and body trim variations.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Prior to 1981, the majority of General Motors vehicles were produced with engines designed by their respective divisions.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] From 1981 onward, GM ended its policy of divisionally developed engines, instead offering engines under a singular GM brand.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] As an exception, Cadillac offers division-exclusive engines (the Northstar and Blackwing V8 engine families).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In 1981, GM lost a 1977 lawsuit related to consumers (who purchased 1977 Oldsmobile Delta 88s equipped with a 350 cu in (5.7 L) Chevrolet small-block engine instead of the 350 cu in (5.7 L) Oldsmobile V8 engine).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] At the time of production, GM had downsized its full-size model lines in preparation for another oil crisis and had increased production of V6 engines as the intended standard engine, underestimating consumer demand for Oldsmobile V8 engines.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] To accommodate the increased market demand, nearly 60% of Delta 88s were equipped with a Chevrolet 5.7 L V8 for 1977.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The lawsuit was filed by the state of Illinois, claiming GM falsely advertised the vehicles.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In 1981, GM settled the lawsuit with the vehicle buyers and discontinued their company-unique policy of division-specific engines.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Prior to the mid-1970s, the American luxury brands Lincoln and Cadillac offered model lines consisting entirely of full-size two-door and four-door sedans and full-size personal luxury cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] At the beginning of the decade, European automakers began to market their largest sedans as luxury vehicles in North America.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In response to both the 1973 oil crisis and to regain lost market share, both Cadillac and Lincoln introduced smaller vehicles for their brand.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In one of the most controversial uses of rebranding in automotive history, both vehicles were derived from smaller GM and Ford divisional model ranges.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] For the 1977 model year, Lincoln released the Lincoln Versailles to match the debut of the Cadillac Seville.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In contrast with the Seville (sharing its chassis underpinnings both the Chevrolet Nova and the Chevrolet Camaro), the Versailles shared nearly its entire body with the Mercury Monarch (itself a counterpart of the Ford Granada); the model line also replaced the previous Mercury Grand Monarch Ghia.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Outsold by the Seville nearly three-to-one, the Versailles sold far under sales predictions and was discontinued early in the 1980 model year.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] For 1982, Cadillac released the Cadillac Cimarron to compete against compact European-brand executive sedans.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The smallest Cadillac produced since the 1900s, the Cimarron used the chassis of the GM J-body four-door sedan.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Developed and brought to market less than a year before the J-body was released, Cadillac was left with almost no time to distinguish the Cimarron from its divisional counterparts from Chevrolet, Buick, Oldsmobile, and Pontiac.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Though sharing nearly its entire exterior with the four-door Chevrolet Cavalier, the Cimarron was priced nearly twice as high as its counterpart.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Additionally, J-body vehicles from other divisions could be equipped nearly identically to the Cimarron for a lower cost.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Though the model line closely matched its Buick Skyhawk and Oldsmobile Firenza counterparts in sales, the Cimarron was discontinued following the 1988 model year.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Though the Lincoln Versailles was largely forgotten after its 1980 discontinuation (its role superseded by the downsizing of the Lincoln Continental for 1982), the Cimarron would cause extensive damage to the Cadillac brand, as its market share declined by almost 50% from 1980 to 1998.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] As of current production, neither Lincoln nor Cadillac has marketed a compact-segment car.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] From 1982 until 1986, the front-wheel drive A platform underpinned the Chevrolet Celebrity, Cutlass Ciera, Pontiac 6000, and Buick Century.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In 1987, Chrysler Corporation acquired American Motors Corporation (AMC) from Renault, leading to the exit of the latter company from the North American market.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] As part of the sale, Chrysler obtained the AMC dealership network, the AMC Eagle line of all-wheel drive cars, and the Jeep line of sport-utility vehicles and pickup trucks.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] For 1989, Chrysler established the Jeep-Eagle Division in a strategy to both focus on Jeep and offer specialty cars differentiated from the established Chrysler lines.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Following the retirement of the AMC Eagle Wagon in early 1988 (derived from the 1971 AMC Hornet), Eagle established its product line with the introduction of the 1988 Premier and Medallion (developed by Renault prior to the sale of AMC).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] To expand the product range beyond the two sedans, Chrysler sourced vehicles from Mitsubishi, introducing the 1989 Summit (Dodge/Plymouth Colt) and 1990 Talon (Mitsubishi Eclipse).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] In contrast to the Jeep range, Eagle was marketed towards consumers interested in imported vehicles.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] For 1992, the Eagle Vision full-size sedan replaced the Premier, becoming the first Eagle-brand vehicle developed by Chrysler.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Positioned between the Dodge Intrepid and Chrysler Concorde, the Eagle Vision shared most exterior trim with the Concorde.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] It was the only Chrysler LH car offered exclusively with a five-passenger interior.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Coinciding with the 1998 Daimler-Chrysler merger, the Eagle brand was discontinued; the singular Jeep brand was integrated as part of Chrysler or Dodge dealership networks.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The Chrysler 300M was originally developed as a second generation of the Eagle Vision; following the discontinuation of Eagle, the vehicle continued into production as a Chrysler model, adopting a slightly restyled grille, Chrysler badging, and a Chrysler interior.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] For the 1989 model year, Toyota and Nissan introduced the Lexus and Infiniti luxury brands in the United States (following the Acura luxury brand of Honda) with the all-new Lexus LS400 and Infiniti Q45 full-size sedans.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Both brands expanded their model line for 1990, sourcing an existing model line from the Japanese market to rebrand as an entry-level offering.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The Lexus ES250 is a four-door sedan derived from the V20 Toyota Camry.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Though visibly similar to the Camry introduced for 1987, the ES250 was a rebranded Toyota Camry Prominent/Vista; a model developed for Japan, the Prominent/Vista (dependent on sales network) is a four-door pillared hardtop sedan with a slightly lower roofline and restyled body panels.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Along with the change to left-hand drive, the ES250 adopted an interior similar to the larger LS (along with similarly styled wheels and taillamps).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The Infiniti M30 is a two-door notchback coupe derived from the Nissan Leopard (a model never sold in North America).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Along with the coupe, Infiniti sold the M30 as a two-door convertible (converted in the United States).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] With the exception of its badging and its dashboard (sourced from the left-hand drive Nissan Skyline), the M30 differed from the Leopard primarily in its steering wheel location.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Intended largely as placeholder models, the ES250 and M30 were largely overshadowed by their companion flagship sedans.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Following the end of the 1992 model year, both models were withdrawn (as their Japanese counterparts had ended their model cycles).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] For 1993, the ES250 was replaced by the ES300; while again sharing its body with a Japanese-market Toyota (Toyota Vista/Windom) and its chassis and engine with the Camry, the ES300 shared no resemblance to the American-market Camry.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Infiniti moved away from a two-door coupe entirely, replacing the M30 with the four-door J30 (Nissan Leopard J Ferie in Japan).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The Rover CityRover, launched in 2003 as the last vehicle from the MG Rover Group, was a rebadged Tata Indica made in India.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] A variant of rebadging is licensing models to be produced by other companies, typically in another country.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The earliest such vehicle was the Austin 7 (1922–1939), designed and built by Austin Motor Company and licensed to other manufacturers across continents, which became their first-ever model.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The Bantam in the US that would eventually build the first Jeep, BMW in Germany, and Nissan in Japan.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Among the post-war cars, the Fiat 124 designed and built by Fiat, Italy was licensed to various other manufacturers from different countries.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] It became a dominant car in many Eastern Europe and West Asian countries.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] The Morris Oxford Series IV built by Morris of England in 1955 would become Hindustan Ambassador in India and was manufactured until 2014.
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] Another example of this is the British Hillman Hunter, which was license-built in Iran as the Paykan, as well as Naza, building vehicles under license from Kia and Peugeot (Naza 206 Bestari).
[src:dodge-ram-van/badge-engineering] A similar example of licensed badge-engineered products would be the Volga Siber, a rebadged version of the Chrysler Sebring sedan and the Dodge Stratus sedan produced in Russia from 2008 until 2010.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] A **box truck**, or **box van**, is a chassis cab truck with an enclosed cuboid-shaped cargo area.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] On most box trucks, the cabin is separate to the cargo area; however some box trucks have a door between the cabin and the cargo area.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] Regular cab box trucks are generally larger than cargo vans but smaller than day cab tractor-trailers with movable trailers.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] Crew cab box trucks tend to be larger than crew vans but smaller than crew cab tractor-trailers with movable trailers.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] The difference between a box truck and a van is that the cargo van is a one-piece (unibody), while a box truck is created by adding a cargo box to a chassis cab.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] The boxes on box trucks are typically 10–26 ft (3.0–7.9 m) in length (the overall length of the box plus cab is even longer) and can range from Class 3 to Class 7 (12,500 lb. to 33,000 lb. gross vehicle weight rating).
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] They often have a garage door-like rear door that rolls up.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] They are often used by companies transporting home appliances or furniture, or are used as moving trucks which can be rented by individuals.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] Ford, Dodge and Chevrolet/GMC have historically been the most common manufacturers of conventional chassis cab (truck cab on chassis without a body) to which the cargo box is attached by various producers (called body builders or upfitters).
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] Isuzu, Fuso and UD Trucks have been the most common producers of cab over-type medium duty chassis cab used as platforms for small box trucks.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] Freightliner, International, Ford, and Hino have been the most common manufacturers of large conventional box trucks.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] Small box trucks often use the cab of full size vans from Ford, Chrysler or General Motors (e.g.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] Ford E-Series/Econoline/Ford Transit, Dodge Ram Van, Chevrolet Express/Chevrolet Van/GMC Vandura/GMC Savana), though pre-manufactured cutaway van chassis vehicles are the basis (rather than an actual cargo van), in order to reduce the labour required for production.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] Large box trucks are based on medium-duty trucks through chassis cab trucks, mostly equipped with air brakes (e.g.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] Ford F-Series, Freightliner Business Class M2, Hino 600 / L-Series, International Durastar / MV).
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] In British English, **box van** is a term for a four-wheeled covered goods wagon (freight vehicle) with a fully enclosed body.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] In British English the word *truck* refers to large open topped freight vehicles or rail freight waggons.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] A *lorry* is defined as a medium or large truck.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] A *van* is used for an enclosed railway freight carriage or medium or smaller commercial road vehicles.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] A **Luton body** is a style of commercial vehicle body incorporating an enclosed box body extended over the cab.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] It takes its name from the town of Luton, in Bedfordshire, where the Bedford commercial vehicle plant was located.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] This style of body was designed to accommodate the high-volume, low-weight loads of straw hats which were part of Luton's industry.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] Straw hats were wrapped in hessian fabric in long cylinders to fit across the width of the van.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] It was incidental that it was the home of Bedford although all the early Luton vans were on Bedford chassis.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] The body style is common in medium commercial vehicles such as the Ford Transit, as well as larger vehicles, especially those used by household removals companies as well as larger moving trucks from U-Haul.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] More modern examples may be streamlined to reduce wind resistance.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] Some commercial vehicles have a wind deflector on the cab roof, but this is not a Luton body; the Luton is functional and can be accessed from the main body.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] Many commercial vehicles have tilting cabs.
[src:dodge-ram-van/box-truck] To allow for this, the floor of the Luton may be hinged, and there may be a hinged flap at the front.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] There are many types of car body styles.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] They vary depending on intended use, market position, location, and the era they were made.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Lightweight off-road vehicle with sparse bodywork.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Originally two- or four-wheeled carriages in the 19th and early 20th centuries pulled by one horse, the motorized buggies were developed in the 1960s and grew in popularity and diversity.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] A convertible allows an open-air driving experience, with the ability to provide a roof when required.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Most convertible roofs are either a folding textile soft-top or a retractable metal roof.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Convertibles with a metal roof are sometimes called 'retractable hardtop', 'coupé convertible', or 'coupé cabriolet'.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Two-door car, seating up to four persons.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Some two-door cars have only two seats, thus **two-seaters**.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Type of SUV with a sloping roofline similar to fastback cars, That is often adopted to offer a styling advantage compared to standard SUVs.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Manufacturers often sell them as more premium models than their standard SUV counterparts.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Vehicle with a higher ground clearence and larger space, That is built in a unibody platform shared with standard cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Originally a North American term used for vehicles that blend characteristics between two types, it evolved to be a term for SUVs built in a unibody chassis, Even though the term SUV is used to refer both to crossovers and standard SUVs due to their visual similarities.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Car with a roofline that slopes continuously down at the back.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] The design features a single unbroken convex curve from the roof to the rear.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Used in the U.S. in the funeral industry to carry flowers for burial services.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Typically a coupé-style, forward-passenger compartment with an open well in the rear.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Car with a hatch-type rear door that is hinged at the roof and opens upwards.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] The term "hatchback" can also refer to that type of rear door, which is also used on several sports cars, SUVs, and large luxury cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] The modification of a passenger car to provide a long cargo area for carrying a coffin or casket.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Hearses often have large glass panels for viewing the coffin.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] A vehicle that combines characteristics and styling of a sedan with a higher ground clearance, Similar to a crossover.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] A Kammback is a car where the rear slopes downwards before being abruptly cut off with a vertical or near vertical surface.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] This reduces the aerodynamic drag, improving the efficiency, while the stil keeping its traditional shape.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Variant of a hatchback where the roof line and the rear cargo door are more horizontal than vertical.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] A luxury-type vehicle that is typically driven by a chauffeur with a partition between the driver's compartment and the passenger's compartment.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Limousines may also be stretched to provide more room in the rear passenger compartment.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] In some European usage, the word describes a regular four-door sedan body style.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Vehicle designed to transport passengers in the rear seating row(s) with reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Typically has a combined passenger and cargo area, a high roof, a flat floor, a sliding door for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] In Europe, some small minivans have been marketed as 'leisure activity vehicles'.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Car with a distinct rear section, With the back of the passenger compartment being in an angle to the top of what is generally the baggage compartment.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] A cargo vehicle based upon passenger car chassis and typically has one row of seats with no side windows at the rear.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] A panel van is smaller than a panel truck or cargo van and is often built on a car platform.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] A panel truck is a larger version of the panel van and is often built on a heavier platform.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] In South Africa, a pickup truck is called a "bakkie".
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] An open two-seat car with emphasis on sporting appearance or character.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Initially, an American term for a two-seat car with no weather protection, usage has spread internationally and has evolved to include two-seat convertibles.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] These form separate compartments for engine, passenger, and cargo.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] A sedan is called a "berlina" in Spanish and Italian, or a "berline" in French.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Initially, a horse-drawn vehicle used to carry shooting parties with their equipment and game; subsequently synonymous with station wagon / estate car; and in contemporary usage a three- or five-door wagon combining features of a station wagon and a coupé.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Type of vehicle that combines characteristics of a passenger car with a offroad vehicle, like higher ground clearence and four wheel drive.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Has a two-box design, a large cargo area, and a rear tailgate that is hinged to open for access to the cargo area.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] The body style is similar to a hatchback car; however, station wagons are longer and are more likely to have the roofline extended to the rear of the car (resulting in a vertical rear surface to the car) to maximize the cargo space.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] In French, a station wagon is called a "break".
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] A semi-convertible style used on some sports cars, featuring a fully removable soft or hard roof panel that leaves the A and B pillars in place on the car body.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Based on a passenger sedan chassis and has a cargo tray in the rear integrated with the passenger body (as opposed to a pickup truck, which has a separate cargo tray).
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] In Australia, the term "ute" was originally used solely for coupé utility cars; however, in recent years, it has also been used for pickup trucks.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Has two rows of raised seats, similar to horse-drawn carriages; usually did not have front doors, a roof, or a windshield.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] The baquet ("bathtub") style was produced in the early 1900s in Europe.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Also a marketing term used on cars built in the United States in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Italian two-seat sports car with either an open-top or convertible roof.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] The term was originally used for lightweight open-top racing cars from the late 1940s through the 1950s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Since the 1950s, the name barchetta ("little boat" in Italian) has been revived on several occasions, mostly for cars with convertible roofs that are not specifically intended for racing.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Italian sports coupé, typically with two seats but also including 2+2 cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] A retractable textile roof, similar to a convertible/cabriolet.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] The difference is that where a convertible often has the B-pillar, C-pillar, and other bodywork removed, the cabrio-coach retains all bodywork to the top of the door frames and just replaces the roof skin with a retractable fabric panel.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Some modern cars, Like the Fiat 500 (2007), featured this body style.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] An external or open-topped driver's position and an enclosed compartment for passengers.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Although the different terms may have once had specific meanings for certain car manufacturers or countries, the terms are often used interchangeably.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Some coupé de villes have the passengers separated from the driver in a fully enclosed compartment, while others have a canopy for the passengers and no partition between the driver and the passengers (therefore passengers enter the compartment via the driver's area).
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Usually describes pillarless hardtops that are cars without a B-pillar often styled to give the appearance of a convertible.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Popular in the United States from the mid 1950s through the mid 1970s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] It also refers to a separate top that is removable and made of metal or other hard material for sports cars or small SUVs.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] A car where the rear passengers are covered by a convertible top.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Often the driver is separated from the rear passengers with a partition, as per a limousine.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] American luxury coupés and convertibles produced from 1952 to 2007.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] The cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] An open-roof automobile without any fixed weather protection, which was popular from the 1900s until the 1930s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] An open-topped roadster body and a rear cargo bed.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] A light, inexpensive, open car with basic bodywork and no windshield, top, or doors.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Most runabouts had just a single row of seats, providing seating for two passengers.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] Body style was a type of automobile body used from 1908 until the mid-1930s, which had a streamlined profile and a folding or detachable soft top.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] The design consists of a hood or bonnet line raised to be level with the car's waistline, resulting in a straight beltline from front to back.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] A style of open car built in the United States that seats four or more people.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-body-style] The style was popular from the early 1900s to the 1930s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Governments and private organizations have developed **car classification** schemes that are used for various purposes including regulation, description, and categorization of cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The International Standard ISO 3833-1977 *Road vehicles – Types – Terms and definitions* also defines terms for classifying cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The following table summarises the commonly used terms of market segments and legal classifications.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Microcars and their Japanese equivalent— kei cars— are the smallest category of automobile.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Microcars straddle the boundary between car and motorbike, and are often covered by separate regulations from normal cars, resulting in relaxed requirements for registration and licensing.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Engine size is often 700 cc (43 cu in) or less, and microcars have three or four wheels.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Microcars are most popular in Europe, where they originated following World War II.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The predecessors to micro cars are voiturettes and cycle cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Kei cars have been used in Japan since 1949.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The smallest category of vehicles that are registered as normal cars is called A-segment in Europe, or "city car" in Europe and the United States.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency defines this category as "minicompact." However, this term is not widely used.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The equivalents of A-segment cars have been produced since the early 1920s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] However, the category increased in popularity in the late 1950s when the original Fiat 500 and BMC Mini were released.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The next larger category of small cars is called B-segment in Europe, supermini in the United Kingdom and subcompact in the United States.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The size of a subcompact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of between 85–99 cubic feet (2,410–2,800 L).
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Since the EPA's smaller minicompact category is not as commonly used by the general public, A-segment cars are sometimes called subcompacts in the United States.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] In Europe and Great Britain, the B-segment and supermini categories do not have any formal definitions based on size.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Early supermini cars in Great Britain include the 1977 Ford Fiesta and Vauxhall Chevette.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] In the United States, the first locally-built subcompact cars were the 1970 AMC Gremlin, Chevrolet Vega, and Ford Pinto.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The largest category of small cars is called *C-segment* or *small family car* in Europe, and *compact car* in the United States.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The size of a compact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of 100–109 cu ft (2.8–3.1 m3).
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] In Europe, the third-largest category for passenger cars is called *D-segment* or *large family car*.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] In the United States, the equivalent term is *mid-size* or *intermediate* cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) defines a mid-size car as having a combined passenger and cargo volume of 110–119 cu ft (3.1–3.4 m3).
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] In Europe, the second-largest category for passenger cars is E-segment / executive car, which are usually luxury cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] In other countries, the equivalent terms are *full-size car* or *large car*, which are also used for relatively affordable large cars that are not considered luxury cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Minivan is an American car classification for vehicles that are designed to transport passengers in the rear seating rows, and have reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The equivalent terms in British English are multi-purpose vehicle (MPV), people carrier, and people mover.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Minivans are often of the "one-box" or "two-box" body configuration, high roofs, flat floors, sliding doors for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Mini MPV is the smallest size of MPVs and the vehicles are often built on the platforms of B-segment hatchback models.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The compact MPV size class includes vehicles between the mini MPV and large MPV (minivan) sizes.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Compact MPVs remain predominantly a European phenomenon, although they are also built and sold in many Latin American and Asian markets.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The largest size of minivans is also referred to as "large MPV" and became popular following the introduction of the 1984 Renault Espace and Dodge Caravan.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Since the 1990s, the smaller compact MPV and mini MPV sizes of minivans have also become popular.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] If the term "minivan" is used without specifying a size, it usually refers to a large MPV.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The premium compact class (also called subcompact executive) is the smallest category of luxury cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] It became popular in the mid-2000s, when European manufacturers — such as Audi, BMW, and Mercedes-Benz — introduced new entry-level models that were smaller and cheaper than their compact executive models.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] A compact executive car or a compact luxury car is a premium car larger than a *premium compact* and smaller than an *executive car*.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Compact executive cars are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] In North American terms, close equivalents are "luxury compact" and "entry-level luxury car", although the latter is also used for the smaller *premium compact cars*.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] An executive car is a premium car larger than a *compact executive* and smaller than a *full-size luxury* car.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Executive cars are classified as E-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] In the United States and several other countries, the equivalent categories are full-size car (not to be confused with the European category of "full-size luxury car") or *mid-size luxury* car.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The largest size of a luxury car is known as a *luxury saloon* in the United Kingdom and a *full-size luxury car* in the United States.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] These cars are classified as F-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Vehicles in this category are often the flagship models of luxury car brands.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Cars that prioritize handling or straight-line acceleration are called sports cars or performance cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] However the term "sports car" is also sometimes used specifically for lightweight two-seat cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Sports/performance cars can either be built on unique platforms or upgraded versions of regular cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The definitions for these categories are often blurred and a car may be a member of multiple categories.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Sports cars are designed to emphasize handling, performance, or the thrill of driving.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Sports cars originated in Europe in the early 1900s, with one of the first recorded usages of the term "sports car" being in *The Times* newspaper in the United Kingdom in 1919.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Sports cars started to become popular during the 1920s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The term was originally used for two-seat roadsters (cars without fixed roofs).
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] However, since the 1970s the term has also been used for cars with fixed roofs (which were previously considered grand tourers).
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] A *sports sedan* — also known as "sports saloon" — is a subjective term for a sedan/saloon car that is designed to have sporting performance or handling characteristics.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] A supercar – also called an exotic car – is a loosely defined description of certain high-performance sportscars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Since the 1990s or 2000s, the term "hypercar" has come into use for the highest-performing supercars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Passenger vehicles with off-road capability or styling features are often categorized as either off-road vehicles, sports utility vehicles, or crossover SUVs.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] There are no commonly agreed boundaries between these categories, and usage of the terms varies between countries.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The earliest type of passenger vehicle is called an "off-roader", "four-by-four" or "four-wheel drive".
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Off-road vehicles are usually more focused on off-road capability than SUVs and crossover SUVs (often compromising their on-road ride quality or handling).
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Common features of off-road vehicles are four-wheel drive, high ground clearance, a body-on-frame (separate chassis) construction and low-range gearing.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] A sports utility vehicle (SUV) combines elements of road-going passenger vehicles with features from off-road vehicles, such as raised ground clearance and four-wheel drive.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] There is no common definition of an SUV, and usage varies between countries.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Some definitions claim that an SUV must be built on a light-truck chassis.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] However, a broader definition considers any vehicle with off-road design features as an SUV.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] In some countries — such as the United States — SUVs have been classified as "light trucks", resulting in more lenient regulations compared to passenger vehicles.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The predecessors to SUVs date back to military and low-volume models from the late 1930s, and the four-wheel drive station wagons / carryalls that began to be introduced in 1949.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The 1984 Jeep Cherokee (XJ) is considered to be the first SUV in the modern style.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Most SUVs produced today use unibody construction (as per passenger cars).
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] However, in the past, many SUVs used body-on-frame construction.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] A crossover SUV— also called a crossover or CUV— is a type of sports utility vehicle (SUV) that uses a unibody construction.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Crossovers are often based on a platform shared with a passenger car, as a result, they typically have better comfort and fuel economy, but less off-road capability (many crossovers are sold without all-wheel drive) than truck-based SUVs, though more so than passenger four wheels.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] There are various inconsistencies about whether vehicles are considered crossovers or SUVs, therefore the term SUV is often used as a catch-all for both crossovers and SUVs.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] These classifications can be based on body style (e.g. sedan, coupe or hatchback), number of doors or seating capacity.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Government departments often create classification systems for taxation or regulating vehicle usage (e.g. vehicles that require a specific license or are restricted to certain roads).
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Some jurisdictions may determine vehicle tax based upon environmental principles, such as the user pays principle.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] In Australia, the Federal Chamber of Automotive Industries publishes its classifications.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] A similar set of classes is used by the Canadian EPA.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The classification of a three-box vehicle (sedan) is determined by its length, while the classification of a two-box car (hatchback and SUV) or MPV is determined by its wheelbase.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] In the United Kingdom, a vehicle is taxed according to the vehicle's construction, engine, weight, type of fuel, and emissions, as well as the purpose for which it is used.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] In the United States, since 2010 the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety has used a formula it developed that takes into account a combination of both vehicle footprint (length times width) and weight.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The United States National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) separates vehicles into classes by the curb weight of the vehicle with standard equipment including the maximum capacity of fuel, oil, coolant, and air conditioning, if so equipped.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The United States Federal Highway Administration has developed a classification system used for automatically calculating road use tolls.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] There are two broad categories depending on whether the vehicle carries passengers or commodities.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Vehicles that carry commodities are further subdivided by the number of axles and number of units, including both power and trailer units.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (US EPA) has developed a classification system used to compare fuel economy among similar vehicles.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Passenger vehicles are classified based on a vehicle's total interior passenger and cargo volumes.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Trucks are classified based on their gross vehicle weight rating (GVWR).
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Heavy-duty vehicles are not included in the EPA scheme.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Certain cities in the United States in the 1920s chose to exempt electric-powered vehicles because officials believed those vehicles did not cause "substantial wear upon the pavements".
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in North America.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Cars from these segments may also be sold in other countries.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to North America.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Muscle car is an American term for high-performance cars, usually rear-wheel drive and fitted with a large and powerful V8 engine.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The term originated for the 1960s and early 1970s special editions of mass-production cars which were designed for drag racing.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Pony car is an American class of automobile launched and inspired by the Ford Mustang in 1964.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] It broke all post-World War II automobile sales records, "creating the 'pony car' craze soon adopted by competitors." The term describes an affordable, compact, highly styled car with a sporty or performance-oriented image.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] A personal luxury car is a North American market segment for premium coupé or convertible produced from 1952–2007.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] These two-door cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Not prioritizing maximum interior space, interior volumes are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification, and exterior dimensions can exceed F-segment.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] A sporting version of an affordable compact car or a subcompact car.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] There is no precise definition and the description is applied for marketing purposes to a wide variety of models.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Cars began to be marketed as sport compacts in the mid-1980s when it was used for option packages on American-built coupes.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Since then, it has also been used for standalone sports car models and cars imported from Europe and Asia.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] However, sport compacts are not restricted to just hatchback body styles.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in Europe.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to Europe.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] A grand tourer (GT) is a car that is designed for high-speed and long-distance driving, due to a combination of performance and luxury attributes.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The most common format is a front-engine, rear-wheel-drive two-door coupé with either a two-seat or a 2+2 arrangement.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] The term derives from the Italian language phrase *gran turismo* which became popular in the English language from the 1950s, evolving from fast touring cars and streamlined closed sports cars during the 1930s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Hot hatch (shortened from hot hatchback) is a high-performance version of a mass-produced hatchback car.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] However, factory high-performance versions of hatchbacks have been produced since the 1970s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Front-mounted petrol engines, together with front-wheel drive, are the most common powertrain layout.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] However, all-wheel drive has become more commonly used since around 2010.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-classification] Most hot hatches are manufactured in Europe or Asia.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] A **car platform** is a shared set of common design, engineering, and production efforts, as well as major components, over a number of outwardly distinct models and even types of cars, often from different, but somewhat related, marques.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] It is practiced in the automotive industry to reduce the costs associated with the development of products by basing those products on a smaller number of platforms.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] This further allows companies to create distinct models from a design perspective on similar underpinnings.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] A car platform is not to be confused with a platform chassis, although such a chassis can be part of an automobile's design platform, as noted below.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] A basic definition of a platform in cars, from a technical point of view, includes underbody and suspensions (with axles) — where the underbody is made of the front floor, rear floor, engine compartment, and frame (reinforcement of underbody).
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Platform sharing is a product development method where different products and the brand attached share the same components.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] The purpose with platform sharing is to reduce the cost and have a more efficient product development process.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] The companies gain on reduced procurement costs by taking advantage of the commonality of the components.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] However, this also limits their ability to differentiate the products and imposes a risk of losing the tangible uniqueness of the product.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] The companies have to make a trade-off between reducing their development costs and the degree of differentiation of the products.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Platform sharing is a practice commonly employed by various brands within a corporate group.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] The fundamental components of a shared platform typically include the chassis and the drive unit.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Platform sharing facilitates the efficient production and development of vehicles by leveraging common components across different models, thereby reducing costs and enhancing operational efficiency.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] One of the first car companies to use this product development approach was General Motors in 1908.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] General Motors used a single chassis for certain class of model across most of its brands like Chevrolet, Buick, Pontiac and Oldsmobile.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Later, Chrysler Corporation would do the same for Plymouth, DeSoto and Dodge cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Ford followed the same principle for Ford and Mercury in US markets.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] The chassis unit was common with many shared mechanical components while the exterior styling and interior trims were designed according to its individual brand and category.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Pictured below is the Nissan MS platform, where designs including 5-door hatchback, sedan, compact SUV and minivan were built on a common floor panel and many shared functional assemblies such as engine, transmission and chassis components.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Many vendors refer to this as **product or vehicle architecture**.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] The concept of product architecture is the scheme by which the function of a product is allocated to physical components.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] The car platform strategy has become important in new product development and in the innovation process.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] The finished products have to be responsive to market needs and to demonstrate distinctiveness while – at the same time – they must be developed and produced at low cost.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Adopting such a strategy affects the development process and also has an important impact on an automaker's organizational structure.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] A platform strategy also offers advantages for the globalization process of automobile firms.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Because automakers spend the majority of time and money on the development of platforms, platform sharing affords manufacturers the ability to cut costs on research and development by spreading it over several product lines.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Manufacturers are then able to offer products at a lower cost to consumers.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Additionally, economies of scale are increased, as is return on investment.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Originally, a "platform" was a literally shared chassis from a previously-engineered vehicle, as in the case for the Citroën 2CV platform chassis used by the Citroën Ami and Citroën Dyane, as well as the Volkswagen Beetle frame under the Volkswagen Karmann Ghia.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] These two manufacturers made different category of vehicles under using the same chassis design at different years though the primary vehicle was still in production.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] In the United States, platform sharing has been a common practice since the 1960s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] This was when GM used the same platform in the development of the Pontiac LeMans, the Buick Skylark, the Chevrolet Chevelle, and the Oldsmobile Cutlass.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] In the 1980s, Chrysler's K-cars all wore a badge with the letter "K" to indicate their shared platform.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] In later stages, the "K" platform was extended in wheelbase, as well as use for several of the Corporation's different models.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] In the same decade, Fiat and Saab jointly developed cars using the Type Four platform to compete with the German-dominated European executive car segment.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] General Motors used similar strategies with its "J" platform that debuted in mid-1981 in four of GM's divisions.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Subsequently, GM introduced its "A" bodies for the same four divisions using the same tread width/wheelbase of the "X" body platform, but with larger bodywork to make the cars seem larger, and with larger trunk compartments.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] They were popular through the 1980s, primarily.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Even Cadillac started offering a "J" body model called the Cimarron, a much gussied-up version of the other four brands' platform siblings.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] A similar strategy applied to what is known as the N-J-L platform, arguably the most prolific of GM's efforts on one platform.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Once more, GM's four lower-level divisions all offered various models on this platform throughout the 1980s and into the 1990s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] The 1988 Fiat Tipo was one of the first European cars utilizing a modular platform, also used for the Fiat Tempra.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Japanese carmakers have followed the platform sharing practice with Honda's Acura line, Nissan's Infiniti brand, and Toyota's Lexus marque, as the entry-level luxury models are based on their mainstream lineup.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] For example, the Lexus ES is essentially an upgraded and rebadged Toyota Camry.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] After Daimler-Benz merged with Chrysler, Chrysler engineers used several M-B platforms for new models including the Crossfire which was based on the M-B SLK roadster.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Other models that share platforms are the European Ford Focus, Mazda 3, and the Volvo S40.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Differences between shared models typically involve styling, including headlights, tail lights, and front and rear fascias.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Examples also involve differing engines and drivetrains.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Platform sharing *may* be less noticeable now; however, it is still very apparent.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Vehicle architectures primarily consist of "under the skin" components, and shared platforms can show up in unusual places, like the Nissan FM platform-mates Nissan 350Z marketed as a sports car and Infiniti FX positioned as a SUV.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] The Volkswagen A platform-mates such as the sports-oriented Audi TT and the economy-focused Volkswagen Golf also share much of their mechanical components but are visually entirely different.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Both the Volkswagen Group and Toyota have had much success building many well-differentiated vehicles from many marques, from the same platforms.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] One of the least conspicuous recent examples is the Chevy Trailblazer and Chevy SSR; both use the GMT-360 platform.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Platform sharing allows for fewer parts for different models of vehicles and therefore the task of inventorying those parts is greatly reduced.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Platform sharing allows manufacturers to cover many different market segments when a platform sharing strategy is implemented.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] They are essentially the same vehicles, but they are targeted as being in the mass-market, near luxury, and luxury vehicles segments.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Platform sharing allows manufacturers to design parts with fewer variation.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] A byproduct of this is increased quality, which results in lower defect rates.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Platform sharing allows manufacturers to design flexible platforms that can be tailored to a country's specific needs without compromising quality.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] It also allows for manufacturing standardization and improved logistics.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Platform sharing allows manufacturers to build/design differentiated products faster and cheaper.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] This is possible because the development and cost of the original platform have already been paid for.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Manufacturers that practice platform sharing have the ability to create several models based on the same design but with different names.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] This leads to the public looking over certain models and cannibalized sales from competing automakers with essentially similar products.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] The two elements of platforms are constant and non-constant.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] If the non-constant elements are not designed to be easily integrated into the constant elements of the platform, extensive and expensive changes will have to be made in order to make the elements compatible again.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Failure to do so negates the purpose of platform sharing in that it increases costs as opposed to reducing them.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Platform sharing has the ability to be used in too many different models.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] However, in the minds of the consumers, the products may be too similar and more expensive products may be perceived to be cheaper.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] For example, the perceived value of a "luxury" brand may be not as desirable if it is too similar to a mass-market version of the same platform.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] Conversely, platform sharing may increase the price of the economic models.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] The propensity for a higher number of recall is greatly increased with platform sharing.
[src:dodge-ram-van/car-platform] If a defect is found in one model and that model shares its platform with nine other models, the recall would be magnified by ten thus costing the manufacturer more time and money to fix.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The **Dodge Ram Van** (originally the **Dodge B series**) is a range of full-size vans that were produced by Chrysler Corporation from the 1971 to 2003 model years.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The B series replaced the forward control Dodge A100, transitioning to a front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout that shared components with the D series pickup truck and had a conventional exterior hood for engine access.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The model range consisted of a cargo van, a passenger van marketed as the **Dodge Ram Wagon** after introduction of the Ram nameplate for model year 1980, and a cutaway van chassis which was dropped in 1979.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] With a 33-model year production run, the B series / Ram Van is among the longest-lived platforms in American automotive history.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The exterior and chassis saw only gradual changes during that time, with three distinct generations developed.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Alongside its use by Dodge, the full-size van range was rebadged during the 1970s for both Fargo Trucks and Plymouth (marking the debut of the Plymouth Voyager nameplate).
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For the entire production run, Chrysler produced the vans at the now-demolished Pillette Road Truck Assembly plant in Windsor, Ontario, Canada; prior to 1980, the model line was also produced at Saint Louis Assembly in Fenton, Missouri.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] In 2003, the Dodge Sprinter (a rebranding of its Mercedes-Benz namesake) was introduced, replacing the Ram Van.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Built on the B platform (later AB), the Dodge full-size vans entered production for the 1971 model year.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Using a one-welded-piece "Uniframe" design, the platform was lighter and stronger, giving a lower cargo floor than previous American designs.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] While at the expense of noise, vibration, and harshness (NVH), the resulting lower center of gravity improved handling versus competing products with full frames.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Produced over three distinct generations, the B series van utilized the majority of body sheetmetal from 1971 to 2003.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Alongside passenger and cargo vans, the model line also served as a basis for cutaway chassis during the 1970s, serving both commercial markets and as a basis for recreational vehicles.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Though popular in the latter market, Chrysler Corporation would end production of that design as a consequence of its late 1970s financial difficulties.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The relatively limited changes for the model line across its production made the Dodge Ram van popular with fleet buyers, service companies, and upbuilders because of the compatibility of components across various model years.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] In two size extremes to the market segment, Dodge was the first American manufacturer to popularize extended-length passenger vans, with the 1971 "Maxiwagon" introducing 15-passenger seating.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Conversely, the Ram van was the final full-size short-wheelbase van, as the 109-inch wheelbase B1500 was offered through 2003.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] From 1971 to 1978, Dodge produced two models of the B series van: the **Dodge Tradesman** cargo van and the **Dodge Sportsman** passenger van.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] In line with the D-series pickup truck (which underwent a final redesign for 1972), the van was marketed with three payload series: ½-ton "100", ¾-ton "200", and 1-ton "300".
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Only five inches longer than its A100/A108 predecessor, moving the front axle forward allowed for a substantial increase in interior space.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Dodge introduced the Tradesman and Sportsman in two wheelbases: 109 inches and 127 inches.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Initially introduced in two body lengths, an extended-length "Maxivan/Maxiwagon" variant was introduced during 1971.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Consisting of an 18-inch rear body extension, the Sportsman Maxiwagon could be fitted with four rows of rear seats, allowing for up to 15 passengers.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] While the Tradesman was offered strictly as a cargo van, the Sportsman was offered in three distinct trims: Sportsman, Custom Sportsman, and Royal Sportsman, with the latter rivaling the Dodge Royal Monaco station wagon in equipment and trim.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Along with its highly sloped hoodline and short front fenders, this generation of the B series van is distinguished by several exterior design features.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] On passenger vans with the 127-inch wheelbase, the front passenger door and the rear side doors are separated by a filler panel (with a small window), with all body lengths (including the Maxiwagon) sharing the same side glass.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The side windows are smaller in size, sharing a beltline with the front door glass.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Sharing its powertrain with the Dodge D-series pickup truck (redesigned for 1972), the van line was initially released with a 198 cubic-inch Slant-6 along with a 225 cubic-inch Slant-6 and a 318 cubic-inch V8.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1972, the 198 was dropped with a 360 V8 becoming a second optional V8.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1976, B200 and B300 vans gained the option of big-block 400 and 440 cubic-inch V8s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] A three-speed manual was standard, with the options of a 4-speed manual (added in 1976) and a 3-speed automatic.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] During its production, the first-generation vans saw gradual changes added each year.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1972, front disc brakes were added along with full chrome door handles (replacing black push buttons).
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1973, electronic ignition replaced the previous points-type system and power brakes became standard.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1974, a redesigned plastic grille was added (moving the Dodge lettering to the hood).
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] To better match its Ford and GM competitors, the model line received a sliding door; initially offered on Maxivans/Maxiwagons, the configuration later became an option for the entire model line.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1975, a new single-piece rear door became an option for Sportsman vans; the side-opening door remained unique to the B series line through the end of its production.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] 1976 saw the launch of the Street Van customization package for Tradesman vans (see below), with minor interior revisions; in 1977, the single-panel rear door became standard on all Sportsman vans.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1978, the B series van began a two-year transition towards its second generation.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Much of the body behind of the rear doors was revised, deleting the filler panel of long-wheelbase vans; the side and rear windows now extended slightly below the beltline of the front doors; and the taillamps were enlarged, switching from a horizontal orientation to a vertical one.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The interior underwent a major revision with an all-new dashboard, trim, and seats; upgraded interior controls were now shared with Chrysler cars.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] In another revision, smaller engine covers increased space for front-seat passengers.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The extended-length Maxivan/Maxiwagon was now a 26-inch extension, with the Maxiwagon receiving wraparound corner windows to improve visibility.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] During the last two years of its existence, Fargo offered a rebadged variant of the Tradesman and Sportsman in Canada for 1971 and 1972 only.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Plymouth also received a rebadged variant of the Sportsman, called the Voyager for the 1974 model year.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] While never as popular as the Dodge version, Plymouth marketed the Voyager in this format through 1983, after which the nameplate was transferred to the new minivan that was introduced for 1984 as a rebadged Dodge Caravan.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1979, Dodge completed the two-year transition to its second-generation B series vans, with the front portion of the body undergoing a redesign.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The front fascia received a taller hoodline and grille (styled in line with Dodge Ram pickup trucks), with parking lamps wrapping into the front fenders.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Higher-trim Sportsman vans were fitted with four rectangular headlamps while lower-trim versions (and Tradesman cargo vans) were fitted with dual round headlamps.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] In a change that would prove beneficial to Chrysler, the government reclassified the Sportsman passenger van as a truck (instead of a passenger car), substantially increasing the ability of the company to meet CAFE implementation.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] After 1980, production ended at Saint Louis North Assembly (retooled to produce the Chrysler K cars), with all production subsequently sourced from Pillette Road Truck Assembly.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1980, the windows were revised, with sliding side doors receiving a single-pane window (in line with the single-panel rear door).
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1981, the model line underwent a major rebranding.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] In line with its pickup truck counterpart (which became the Dodge Ram pickup), the Dodge Tradesman and Sportsman nameplates were retired in favor of Dodge Ram Van and Wagon; the B series nomenclature remained, revised to B150, B250, and B350.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Derived from the B150, the Mini-Ram was a higher-trim passenger van with a larger fuel tank.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1984, the Dodge Mini Ram and the Plymouth Voyager were retired from the B series line, as both nameplates became part of the Chrysler minivan line; Plymouth would not again offer a full-size truck prior to its discontinuation.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1986, the grille and badging trim were revised in line with Ram pickup trucks.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] In a safety upgrade, outboard seating positions received 3-point seatbelts for 1992.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1994, the model line underwent its most substantial revision and facelift since 1978.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Distinguished by new front sheetmetal (adopting a grille styled in line with the redesigned Dodge Ram pickup trucks), the body shell underwent structural enhancements to improve crash protection.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] To modernize its appearance, exterior chrome brightwork was reduced (limited to the bumpers and grille).
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] While the dashboard introduced for 1978 remained carryover, the interior saw revisions to the door panels and seats.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] In a branding change, the van line adopted the nomenclature of the Dodge Ram pickup trucks, becoming the B1500, B2500, and B3500.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1995, a driver-side airbag was added.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For the second-generation Ram vans, several changes were made to the powertrain line.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Following the retirement of the big-block 400 and 440 V8s by Chrysler, the 360 V8 (found in 3/4-ton and 1-ton vans) now served as the largest-displacement engine (doing so through 2003).
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The long-running 225 Slant-Six, found in half-ton and 3/4-ton vans, returned as the standard engine (later advertised in its 3.7 L metric displacement); for 1988, it was replaced by a 3.9 L LA V6 adopted from the Dodge Dakota.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The 318 (later 5.2 L) returned as the standard V8 option for all models, adopting fuel injection for 1988 (the 5.9 L V8 doing so for 1989).
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1992, the "Magnum" generation of the 3.9 L and 5.2 L engines was introduced, featuring multiport fuel injection; the 5.9 L followed suit for 1993.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1979, Dodge planned to offer the Mitsubishi 4.0 L (243 CID) inline-six diesel engine (offered as an option on Dodge pickup trucks), but the option was shelved.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1980, the 3-speed column-shifted manual was retired in favor of the overdrive-equipped 4-speed (floor-shifted) manual.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1988, the standard transmission became a 5-speed manual (with the 3.9 L V6); a 4-speed automatic became optional for the V6 and the 5.2 L V8, with a heavy-duty 4-speed automatic for the 5.9 L V8 added for 1990.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] As part of the 1994 update, manual transmissions were discontinued; Dodge became the final full-size van line to standardize automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] In 1991, Chrysler began development of a CNG-fueled version of the Ram Van, using the 5.2 L V8.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] After a short initial prototype production period, the variant was launched into larger-scale production for 1992; approximately 2,000 were produced primarily for fleet sales.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] From 1994 to 1998, Chrysler continued development with CNG powertrains using the Dodge Caravan.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1998, the third-generation B series van was released.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The most substantial revision of the model line since 1971, the body structure was upgraded to improve crash protection.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Along with further reinforcement of the bodyshell, the powertrain was relocated further forward in the chassis (though wheelbases remained carryover), requiring a longer hood and front fenders.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Alongside the chassis upgrades, the interior underwent its first major redesign since 1978.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Coinciding with its relocation forward, the engine cover was reduced in size, increasing space both between the front seats and for both front-seat passengers.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The dashboard was redesigned, both to allow for the introduction of dual airbags and shared componentry with contemporary Chrysler vehicles.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The front doors were distinguished by the deletion of the front vent windows, with the sideview mirrors relocated in their place (shared with the Dodge Ram/Dodge Dakota.To free up interior cargo space, the spare tire was moved from the interior to an underfloor location.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Through its production, the third-generation van saw few functional changes following its 1998 introduction.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Carrying over the 3.9 L V6, 5.2 L V8, and 5.9 L V8 from the 1994 model revision, a 3-speed automatic was paired with the V6 and a 4-speed automatic was paired with the V8 engines.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] V8 engines were now standard on 3/4-ton and one-ton vans.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 2003, the final model year of the Ram vans, the Ram 1500 van received rear vented disc brakes, becoming the only model of the B series to use a rear disc brake setup.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The passenger van models were also discontinued.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Dodge vans, particularly Tradesman vans from the 1971–1977 model years, were very popular as the basis for many custom vans during the custom van craze that occurred during the mid-to-late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Dodge capitalized on this craze, creating a factory customization package called the "Street Van" package.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1976 and 1977 only, the YH3 Street Van could be ordered with a single driver seat, no dash pad, plain steering wheel, and Street Van door decal delete.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The decals were placed in the glovebox at time of manufacture.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Most of these were sent to conversion companies to be customized to customer specification.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] This package was available from the 1976 model year until it was discontinued in the early 1980s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] This was not an overly popular option from the factory, and Street Vans are somewhat rare.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The chrome-plated metal Street Van emblems found on later Street Vans (emblems through mid-1978 were stickers) in good shape are quite valuable to collectors or restorers.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] For 1973, Dodge introduced the Kary Van variant of the B series.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] A factory-produced cutaway van fitted with a cube van rear body, the Kary Van was produced in 10- and 12-foot lengths and two widths (derived from single- or dual-rear-wheel axle configuration).
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Derived from the B300 Tradesman, the cutaway body of the Kary Van would also serve as a basis underpinning bodies for Type C recreational vehicles during the 1970s.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] In 1979, Chrysler ended production of the variant in response to its financial difficulties.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The Dodge 50 series is a light commercial vehicle that was built by Chrysler Europe (and later Renault Trucks) from 1979 to 1993.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Using the cab assembly of the 1971–1978 Dodge Kary Van, the Dodge 50 mated the American-designed cab with a British-designed chassis.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] The model line was powered by Peugeot/Renault gasoline engines and Perkins 4-cylinder diesel engines.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Following the collapse of Chrysler Europe, the model line continued to be manufactured by Renault, which phased out the Dodge branding entirely after 1987.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] After 1993, Renault phased out the model line in favor of its own Renault Master.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] In 2012, Chrysler's Ram brand revived the Tradesman nameplate as the Dodge Grand Caravan C/V cargo van was rebranded as the Ram C/V Tradesman.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] Sold only as a two-passenger cargo van, the Tradesman replaced the rear side windows with metal panels and was fitted with a flat rear load floor.
[src:dodge-ram-van/dodge-ram-van] After 2015, the Ram ProMaster City (based on the Fiat Doblò) replaced the C/V Tradesman.
